430
00:52:55,764 --> 00:53:06,608
So if you're a parent like myself whose kids go to school there right now and will not see the future of this building, what we hear is, I wish this started 10 years ago.

431
00:53:06,628 --> 00:53:07,788
Me too.

432
00:53:09,609 --> 00:53:14,610
And what will this be like for my children while they're learning through construction, right?

433
00:53:14,650 --> 00:53:19,012
And so that's where the modular conversation gets really anxious.

434
00:53:20,823 --> 00:53:30,670
What you also hear is like, because people don't want their kids learning in trailers, even though they have heat and air conditioning, which is like more than we can say for some of the rooms in the building, right?

435
00:53:31,250 --> 00:53:40,017
But you also hear about the reasons kids feel like they belong at Medford High, whether that's athletics that could be disrupted, whether that's

436
00:53:40,577 --> 00:53:44,559
the swim team where like a renovation of the pool will take it out of commission.

437
00:53:44,599 --> 00:53:46,819
And so we have to think about what those alternatives are.

438
00:53:47,400 --> 00:53:53,962
Or if it's your student is in a vocational program that like cannot learn in just any classroom.

439
00:53:54,002 --> 00:53:54,222
Right.

440
00:53:54,542 --> 00:53:59,264
So there's a lot of concern about like the staging and the phasing for those folks.

441
00:53:59,824 --> 00:54:01,665
And it's those are real valid concerns.

442
00:54:02,025 --> 00:54:03,646
We're just not there yet.

443
00:54:04,026 --> 00:54:07,027
Like that's for schematic design and that's for

444
00:54:07,682 --> 00:54:09,563
like the construction planning process.

445
00:54:10,103 --> 00:54:14,365
So there's like concepts of how those things will happen right now and no answers.

446
00:54:14,405 --> 00:54:16,746
And I can sort of appreciate that that's like really uncomfortable.

447
00:54:17,726 --> 00:54:25,670
If we're hearing from folks with very young children, they're like, hurry up, finish this project as fast as you can, because I want my kids to go to this school.

448
00:54:25,690 --> 00:54:27,011
And I'm really excited.

449
00:54:27,031 --> 00:54:34,474
If you're talking to people with very young children, they're super excited about the MFN having the support that it needs.

450
00:54:34,890 --> 00:54:41,317
and the consolidation of the pre-K programs to do a little bit more than we're able to do today with pre-K.

451
00:54:42,098 --> 00:54:53,651
If you hear from folks whose kids have already gone there, there's sort of a mix of reactions, which include, like, again, I wish you did this 10 years ago so my kid could have experienced it.

452
00:54:56,102 --> 00:54:59,305
gee, this is long overdue and I'm with you.

453
00:55:00,045 --> 00:55:10,154
And then I think, you know, you do hear sort of across all of those groups of folks that they are concerned about how much it's going to cost.

454
00:55:10,214 --> 00:55:15,398
And I think that's a real concern and it is something that we'll have to grapple with together.

455
00:55:15,418 --> 00:55:23,305
One of the reasons that we waited, honestly, to do this project is so that we could participate with MSBA and all of the

456
00:55:23,925 --> 00:55:28,389
funding that they're going to provide to us by following through with their programming, right?

457
00:55:29,890 --> 00:55:36,035
So that's a big portion of this, but I think the picture of how this gets paid for is really complicated.

458
00:55:36,756 --> 00:55:44,382
And anybody who tells you like today that they know what that number will be, those are estimates too, right?

459
00:55:44,502 --> 00:55:45,883
And those are estimates based on

460
00:55:46,572 --> 00:55:50,597
No feedback yet from the MSBA about what they will cost share in.

461
00:55:51,157 --> 00:55:55,302
Those estimates are based on really sort of incomplete decisions about space.

462
00:55:56,463 --> 00:56:00,508
And very, very, very high level estimates that'll get refined further.

463
00:56:00,568 --> 00:56:04,252
So there's a million variables that will go into how

464
00:56:05,213 --> 00:56:08,074
how much this building costs.

465
00:56:08,514 --> 00:56:11,135
I do think the numbers sort of take people back.

466
00:56:11,175 --> 00:56:19,557
Like it's surprising to me that we are talking about a building that at the last estimate was like in the $800 million range.

467
00:56:20,357 --> 00:56:22,398
Nothing unusual is happening here in Medford.

468
00:56:22,438 --> 00:56:26,419
This is happening in every school community and school building across the state.

469
00:56:27,534 --> 00:56:35,362
What we have going on here is even more complicated, because vocational programming is always much more expensive than a traditional classroom.

470
00:56:35,382 --> 00:56:37,864
So you can't compare us to Lexington.

471
00:56:38,345 --> 00:56:46,353
Even though they were the most expensive school, that's true until the next school comes along, essentially, is where the trends are in school construction.

472
00:56:47,781 --> 00:56:51,407
So I think there's a lot of conversation that people want to have about cost.

473
00:56:51,967 --> 00:56:53,350
And I completely get it.

474
00:56:53,370 --> 00:56:54,471
I appreciate it.

475
00:56:54,972 --> 00:56:56,294
And I think we will get there.

476
00:56:56,374 --> 00:57:01,482
But it's one of those things where I, if I could like encourage people to do one thing, it's just like.

477
00:57:02,016 --> 00:57:11,861
stick with us a little while longer before we start to worry too much, because we are still talking about really, really, really preliminary information.

478
00:57:13,382 --> 00:57:17,845
So I've had people say, Jenny, this is going to cost me $20,000 a year.

479
00:57:17,865 --> 00:57:19,966
Jenny, this is going to cost me $6,000 a year.

480
00:57:20,886 --> 00:57:22,347
None of those numbers are true.

481
00:57:22,767 --> 00:57:31,212
And I can almost promise you that every single number that I've heard so far is not the actual number, because there's so many variables that we still just don't know about.

482
00:57:32,392 --> 00:57:35,134
So we're waiting on feedback from the MSBA, which we're expecting any day.

483
00:57:35,154 --> 00:57:47,463
And even that will give us an idea of what is to come, but it won't give us all those final answers again until we get through the schematic design process and into like February of next year.

484
00:57:48,260 --> 00:58:04,657
I really appreciate that you guys are thinking about cost to our families and also being very graceful and very delicate with not putting numbers out there that are misleading or not making decisions based on information that we don't know for sure yet.

485
00:58:05,637 --> 00:58:15,100
Because, I mean, I think a worry that a lot of parents brought up last night was that we would start cutting based on numbers that we're not sure about and then we'd have those options off the table forever.

486
00:58:16,121 --> 00:58:20,362
And my understanding is that we have until October when it's pencils down.

487
00:58:20,382 --> 00:58:22,003
Can you explain that really quickly?

488
00:58:22,023 --> 00:58:22,323
Sure.

489
00:58:22,903 --> 00:58:23,043
Yeah.

490
00:58:23,123 --> 00:58:26,444
I think two things happened last night that I think were important.

491
00:58:27,025 --> 00:58:34,087
One was we gave the project team some clear instructions about what we wanted them to cost and how.

492
00:58:35,007 --> 00:58:42,701
And we asked them specifically for some consistency across the options around things like parking the pool.

493
00:58:43,898 --> 00:58:55,811
the auditorium and then a handful of programs that are like sort of outside of the school day kind of programs, like central administration, for example, is like sort of separately listed.

494
00:58:57,132 --> 00:59:06,001
So we gave them some clear direction on how we wanted that cost to be presented back to us so that when anybody looks at those numbers, they can say,

495
00:59:06,922 --> 00:59:11,083
If I take that away, I can be clear about what I'm taking away, right?

496
00:59:11,183 --> 00:59:16,324
The first version was a little bit less clear, so this next version should be super clear.

497
00:59:16,764 --> 00:59:18,164
And like parking is a good example.

498
00:59:18,444 --> 00:59:20,664
Surface parking, cheap, right?

499
00:59:20,844 --> 00:59:21,184
Cheaper.

500
00:59:23,185 --> 00:59:25,865
But we, on that site, we have some opportunities.

501
00:59:25,965 --> 00:59:28,346
So we could put a parking garage.

502
00:59:28,486 --> 00:59:35,967
I don't think that really excites anybody, but what it does do is make way on the site for other things to be possible.

503
00:59:37,103 --> 00:59:39,150
increase playing fields.

504
00:59:39,491 --> 00:59:42,522
The other thing that we asked them to do was give us pricing for

505
00:59:43,814 --> 00:59:48,716
a field over parking situation, which Waltham did recently.

506
00:59:48,797 --> 00:59:54,599
So their parking sort of appears underground, but on top of it are multiple playing fields, right?

507
00:59:54,679 --> 00:59:57,701
So that is interesting.

508
00:59:57,761 --> 00:59:58,421
It's intriguing.

509
00:59:58,461 --> 01:00:02,243
If you don't like to look at a, you know, sort of sea of cars, that's kind of nice, right?

510
01:00:02,703 --> 01:00:10,787
But more importantly, like we have like really few opportunities in Medford to increase the green space available to us.

511
01:00:11,439 --> 01:00:14,674
Playing fields are at a premium when you talk about.

512
01:00:15,619 --> 01:00:16,859
athletics in Medford.

513
01:00:17,559 --> 01:00:23,761
And so continuing to explore what is possible there, I think is really important.

514
01:00:23,781 --> 01:00:26,821
And if we just took that off the table last night, it would be gone forever.

515
01:00:26,901 --> 01:00:30,002
We would never be able to really talk about field over parking.

516
01:00:30,502 --> 01:00:37,884
And we would be sort of stuck only talking about a sea of 450 or whatever parking spaces, right?

517
01:00:38,944 --> 01:00:43,105
And we may decide that's what we want, but we don't have to decide right now.

518
01:00:43,925 --> 01:00:47,167
What when we will have to make those decisions is by October.

519
01:00:47,267 --> 01:00:51,849
So we can make them in an iterative fashion as information comes into focus.

520
01:00:52,349 --> 01:01:03,634
But what the team has told us is like pencils down is like October so that the construction manager and architect can really do their costing and

521
01:01:04,848 --> 01:01:07,789
get those numbers into into lock for February.

522
01:01:09,009 --> 01:01:14,290
So that was like, you know, sort of one thing that happened last night was giving people some clear instructions on what we wanted to see.

523
01:01:14,670 --> 01:01:21,392
The other thing that happened last night was we did take up several hundred recommendations to cut space.

524
01:01:22,512 --> 01:01:23,612
Some of them went forward.

525
01:01:24,213 --> 01:01:34,035
Most of the ones presented by the superintendent and the educational leadership team did go forward and they are, that's very natural to be happening at this phase in the process.

526
01:01:35,634 --> 01:01:49,180
The other proposals got tabled by and large, and I think that's fine, and I think what happened last night was the committee heard from everybody saying, we don't have to do this right now, and maybe we shouldn't, right?

527
01:01:50,441 --> 01:02:03,628
So I think that was a really, really good outcome last night to say we all hear and appreciate that there is still refinement yet to happen in this building, absolutely, but the urgency to do it last night

528
01:02:05,069 --> 01:02:08,572
didn't have to be there, and so I think that clarification really changed things for people.

529
01:02:08,632 --> 01:02:20,201
So I think you'll continue to see us refine space as we can, right, as those things come into focus, as there's more time to consider particularly the feedback that we're expecting from MSBA.

530
01:02:20,718 --> 01:02:21,899
That's really helpful to hear.

531
01:02:21,919 --> 01:02:35,949
I think, you know, I have heard from some residents about scope and I think it's been helpful for them to know that there's time to get solid information for us to make choices first and then to hear feedback and adjust the plan to that.

532
01:02:35,969 --> 01:02:50,220
And I think yesterday's meeting also, if folks tuned in, does show that our school team, our educational team, is thinking a lot about how we can use space more efficiently and how we can right size a lot of the space as well.

533
01:02:50,961 --> 01:03:05,118
Um, something that, um, a question I've gotten is just, I mean, I think this is more of a basic project question, um, what criteria or parameters are we using to kind of whittle down these six options to an ideal option?

534
01:03:05,758 --> 01:03:09,623
And I think, uh, kind of going hand in hand with that another question I've gotten is, um,

535
01:03:11,380 --> 01:03:18,882
With the first option, just the code upgrades, does that preserve the programming that's in the high school?

536
01:03:18,922 --> 01:03:22,083
Does it align with our educational plan?

537
01:03:22,563 --> 01:03:37,068
Because something that, in my experience, has been important is, I think being at MHS quite recently, it's become clear that it's hard to get a 21st century education in a building that's

538
01:03:37,588 --> 01:03:38,809
built for the 20th century.

539
01:03:39,529 --> 01:03:49,973
And I think voters, there are people who are kind of finding it hard because they see option A and they're like, this seems much more affordable.

540
01:03:49,993 --> 01:03:58,037
They're also worried that it doesn't kind of achieve all the goals that we want to set for our schools to really make it a state of the art institution.

541
01:03:58,607 --> 01:04:04,570
Yeah, so option A is a code upgrade, and it's really restrictive.

542
01:04:04,710 --> 01:04:06,051
It means nothing changes.

543
01:04:06,551 --> 01:04:14,175
So while we may have to take every wall out and rebuild it inside the school, every wall must go up in its exact current place.

544
01:04:15,036 --> 01:04:23,020
So what that means is, for example, the 55,000 additional square feet that are being planned for vocational expansion.

545
01:04:23,700 --> 01:04:25,862
That cannot happen in a code upgrade.

546
01:04:27,043 --> 01:04:44,199
But more than that, our special education ed plan cannot be met, and the ed plan overall cannot be met by option A. So what that means is if Medford decides to go with option A, that $450 million price tag will be ours to bear 100%.

547
01:04:47,115 --> 01:04:50,977
If it met the Ed plan, that would be different, right?

548
01:04:50,997 --> 01:04:57,019
It's not like code upgrade means never MSBA, but it has to meet the Ed plan.

549
01:04:57,719 --> 01:05:01,260
And we're not talking about like an increment away from the Ed plan.

550
01:05:01,300 --> 01:05:07,583
We're talking about a really big gully between the Ed plan and what the building, the current building can provide.

551
01:05:07,663 --> 01:05:11,424
So that's option A in terms of like,

552
01:05:11,928 --> 01:05:13,229
what is possible, right?

553
01:05:13,269 --> 01:05:16,391
So it's kind of not possible under that.

554
01:05:16,491 --> 01:05:19,473
But all of the other options do meet the ed plan.

555
01:05:20,494 --> 01:05:23,036
And the ed plan is another document that's going to continue to evolve.

556
01:05:23,076 --> 01:05:28,880
So the MSBA is going to come back to us and ask questions and say, gee, you asked for the space, but it doesn't say anything about it in the ed plan.

557
01:05:28,920 --> 01:05:29,861
Why is that, right?

558
01:05:29,901 --> 01:05:41,129
So they're looking at this as like another set of eyes and ears and as people who do this work for a living to say, is there complete alignment in what you're proposing to do so that

559
01:05:42,830 --> 01:05:51,941
We all can feel good that when we go ask our residents to vote on this project that we have sort of left no stone unturned, right?

560
01:05:51,961 --> 01:05:54,905
But yeah, the ed plan is super important.

561
01:05:55,045 --> 01:05:58,569
It's like the anchoring document and it doesn't get a lot of discussion.

562
01:06:00,551 --> 01:06:02,072
But it's really important.

563
01:06:02,192 --> 01:06:04,895
It paints a picture of what education should look like.

564
01:06:05,455 --> 01:06:14,742
And it was written by our educators, but it was written by our educators after many days of meetings with teachers, students, parents, and

565
01:06:16,192 --> 01:06:21,753
There's lots of conversation in our various meetings and in our school committee meetings about the ed plan.

566
01:06:22,233 --> 01:06:28,435
And one of the things that you'll hear again and again is that the students were the real leaders in those conversations.

567
01:06:29,675 --> 01:06:41,537
And they talked about what impedes their day every single day in the current building and where they shine and where they feel like they can't shine.

568
01:06:41,938 --> 01:06:43,618
And the ed plan

569
01:06:44,727 --> 01:06:49,290
is there to be responsive to like moving that dynamic forward.

570
01:06:50,250 --> 01:07:05,679
At the same time like that conversation sort of unveils that like Medford Public Schools has options where to take action now so that we can start to address some of those things even before a building but the building will limit

571
01:07:06,299 --> 01:07:07,399
you know, how far we can go.

572
01:07:07,499 --> 01:07:09,440
So all of those conversations are happening.

573
01:07:09,840 --> 01:07:12,781
There's lots of transformation happening at the high school in particular.

574
01:07:13,781 --> 01:07:16,642
But the building, the building is like a big, huge piece of it.

575
01:07:16,662 --> 01:07:21,503
And we just like, there's, you know, certain times in life where you just can't work around something or somebody.

576
01:07:22,023 --> 01:07:24,183
And like, the building is one of those things.

577
01:07:24,223 --> 01:07:30,925
You just can't, you can't muscle around it to get what you want out of education anymore.

578
01:07:31,345 --> 01:07:31,545
Yeah.

579
01:07:31,725 --> 01:07:34,886
It's too, it's, it's too restrictive.

580
01:07:35,221 --> 01:07:37,442
I definitely have felt that on my time there.

581
01:07:37,502 --> 01:07:47,449
There were times where we, you know, as clubs tried to do things or we tried to get more involved in the nature or have assemblies and it just wasn't possible.

582
01:07:49,410 --> 01:07:57,975
And the other part to the question, sorry, I got a little muddled, but could you give us a sense of what the committee is thinking about when it chooses between the sex options?

583
01:07:57,995 --> 01:07:58,256
Oh, sorry.

584
01:07:58,396 --> 01:08:00,377
I knew there was another part of the question that I forgot.

585
01:08:02,098 --> 01:08:06,521
You know, one of the interesting things about the committee is there's 25 people on the committee.

586
01:08:06,541 --> 01:08:07,902
There are 15 voting members.

587
01:08:08,582 --> 01:08:12,544
And, you know, that's a huge committee, actually.

588
01:08:12,604 --> 01:08:18,088
And people, everyone who I tell that to is like, oh, my, like, how do you manage that big of a committee?

589
01:08:18,108 --> 01:08:19,308
And it's not easy.

590
01:08:19,789 --> 01:08:26,833
But I think what we have done is assemble a group of people who have really varied and broad expertise and interests.

591
01:08:28,735 --> 01:08:32,739
So everyone's gonna come to those decisions a little bit differently.

592
01:08:33,519 --> 01:08:35,261
And I think that's okay.

593
01:08:35,762 --> 01:08:39,345
So we have lots of data and we have lots of facts available to us.

594
01:08:39,846 --> 01:08:44,330
We have a giant evaluation matrix that'll get updated and we'll be able to look at it.

595
01:08:44,430 --> 01:08:45,711
And for those people who like,

596
01:08:46,957 --> 01:08:50,298
need a score, there will be a score, right?

597
01:08:50,678 --> 01:08:57,260
For those people who are like really going to make a choice based on price, that data will be available to them.

598
01:08:57,700 --> 01:09:06,523
For the people who are gonna say what is the best value and how am I optimizing the things that the community is telling me are important, they'll have that choice.

599
01:09:07,043 --> 01:09:13,785
I think in the end, I think there'll be a lot of coalescing around

600
01:09:14,409 --> 01:09:15,931
Maybe one or two options.

601
01:09:17,053 --> 01:09:20,497
I don't know which they'll be, but I'll be interested to see what the community says.

602
01:09:20,558 --> 01:09:29,350
So people really care a lot about what they're hearing in these community meetings and out in the community, people pointing out what they like and what they don't like.

603
01:09:30,591 --> 01:09:35,474
So it will be, it will simply be a majority vote, right, that picks the final winner.

604
01:09:35,534 --> 01:09:41,559
But I think what we have found some success at in the past is being able to like narrow down a bit.

605
01:09:41,699 --> 01:09:50,906
So probably what you'll see us do is say like these two options or three options we're like eliminating and then you can sort of focus the attention a little bit more.

606
01:09:52,187 --> 01:09:54,128
And all of that will happen at our June 10th meeting.

607
01:09:54,751 --> 01:10:03,113
Great, I really appreciate this explanation of where we're at and how folks can get involved in walking us through what you guys are thinking about.

608
01:10:03,193 --> 01:10:05,394
It's really, I think, important for the community here.

609
01:10:05,414 --> 01:10:07,935
Again, it's early days.

610
01:10:09,795 --> 01:10:11,416
There's the June 10th meeting.

611
01:10:11,496 --> 01:10:19,898
There's also time until October for us to really think about the small bits and pieces of the design.

612
01:10:21,079 --> 01:10:23,121
And there's time for the community to get involved as well.

613
01:10:23,141 --> 01:10:24,863
So I'm really grateful for this rundown.

614
01:10:25,024 --> 01:10:25,204
Thanks.

615
01:10:25,224 --> 01:10:25,965
Yeah, no problem.

616
01:10:27,006 --> 01:10:28,688
Any other MSBA questions?

617
01:10:32,152 --> 01:10:39,501
Just on the high school really quickly, I just want to thank you and the SBC for your work and your leadership on this, for commitment to engaging the public extensively.

618
01:10:41,452 --> 01:10:45,516
And I think, you know, just driving home that point that the cost and the price is going to change.

619
01:10:45,576 --> 01:10:48,999
It's going to get lower, likely, as we move through the process.

620
01:10:50,695 --> 01:10:51,976
And that's really important, right?

621
01:10:51,996 --> 01:10:54,459
You've got very high level estimates.

622
01:10:55,039 --> 01:10:56,581
We're going to maximize our efficiencies.

623
01:10:56,621 --> 01:11:01,166
We're going to find exactly which spaces need to be in this building and which ones don't.

624
01:11:02,187 --> 01:11:03,568
But that kind of brings me to my other point.

625
01:11:03,588 --> 01:11:05,090
You brought it up about Lexington.

626
01:11:05,390 --> 01:11:06,751
Lexington's was 660.

627
01:11:07,292 --> 01:11:09,835
And that's basically just a 9 through 12 high school.

628
01:11:09,855 --> 01:11:10,716
That's correct.

629
01:11:10,896 --> 01:11:12,978
And this complex or the things that will be included

630
01:11:13,712 --> 01:11:15,413
You know, they don't have a vocational school.

631
01:11:15,493 --> 01:11:15,913
We do.

632
01:11:16,373 --> 01:11:18,554
They don't have the MFN, Medford Family Network.

633
01:11:18,594 --> 01:11:18,994
We do.

634
01:11:19,374 --> 01:11:21,614
They don't do child care in their building.

635
01:11:21,695 --> 01:11:22,095
We do.

636
01:11:23,455 --> 01:11:25,076
Pre-K, we don't do it there now.

637
01:11:25,156 --> 01:11:25,756
We used to.

638
01:11:25,856 --> 01:11:27,376
That's coming back to Medford High.

639
01:11:27,716 --> 01:11:33,778
But that opens up space in our elementary schools that we need in those buildings.

640
01:11:34,599 --> 01:11:36,339
There's no central offices in Lexington.

641
01:11:36,399 --> 01:11:40,480
They don't have public-facing programs like the Culinary Bistro 489 or cosmetology or

642
01:11:42,721 --> 01:11:53,109
cars and think, you know, their playing fields maybe don't get the same kind of utilization that ours do necessarily either, never mind programs like the Japanese Language School.

643
01:11:54,651 --> 01:11:59,875
And bringing Curtis Tufts finally back to integrated, you know, not having our alternative high school be

644
01:12:00,448 --> 01:12:04,292
far away and separate and in an old building that also needs repair.

645
01:12:04,312 --> 01:12:18,604
So I think when you think about the things that we do in this building right now that we need to keep doing, the things that we want to bring to this building because we'll do them better there and they help us in our other spaces, you just really can't compare this to the other high schools that have been built recently.

646
01:12:19,025 --> 01:12:21,947
And to be honest, when you say Lexington does one thing for $660 million and we do

647
01:12:24,789 --> 01:12:31,692
17 things for 775 million and probably less or 800 or whatever the estimate is right now that's going to come down.

648
01:12:31,712 --> 01:12:35,653
I think that's just really important for folks to be aware of too.

649
01:12:35,713 --> 01:12:38,254
This is not the same as these other projects.

650
01:12:38,894 --> 01:12:40,935
So I know you said that a little bit.

651
01:12:41,055 --> 01:12:44,096
I wanted to just iterate it and reiterate it a little bit more.

652
01:12:45,616 --> 01:12:46,977
And just closing, I think,

653
01:12:49,391 --> 01:12:51,632
One, I think it's really important for us to have an honest convo.

654
01:12:51,652 --> 01:13:11,296
If we're at the end of the day and it's like, well, this option is 650 million and this option is 700 million and one of those options doesn't bring pre-K or has a surface parking but no new field or doesn't bring Curtis Tufts back, you know, maybe we're doing that for 50 million on this site that would cost 100 or 120 million in the long term to try to do that in other places.

655
01:13:11,316 --> 01:13:18,218
So I think folks need to understand that we're really trying to maximize the efficiency to the city in this one project.

656
01:13:18,698 --> 01:13:28,745
And, you know, it might have a bigger price tag but it actually costs less than it would for us to do five or six projects and that to reach those same goals.

657
01:13:28,845 --> 01:13:42,213
So I really appreciate your commitment to maximizing the value for students and for our community spaces and, you know, working really, really diligently to minimize the cost and the tax impact to the taxpayer.

658
01:13:42,253 --> 01:13:44,655
I think like that's the work and you guys are doing it.

659
01:13:45,335 --> 01:13:52,219
And the one thing I really hope to talk about more, I think we can be a partner on, is creative decisions to help fund the project.

660
01:13:52,339 --> 01:13:58,002
And I know there's grants that have been applied for in addition to the hundreds of millions of dollars that we'll get from the MSBA.

661
01:13:59,403 --> 01:14:09,088
But I also think if we're able to build a stadium, a new stadium on the Medford High School site, Hormel is in tough shape and there's millions and millions of dollars that would need to go into that.

662
01:14:09,188 --> 01:14:10,009
I think that's something

663
01:14:10,609 --> 01:14:18,256
We can look at Hormel is right by the highway right by a bunch of residential construction right by some of our main commercial areas.

664
01:14:18,836 --> 01:14:22,239
Maybe that's a place where we could look at a land lease from the city.

665
01:14:22,419 --> 01:14:24,200
We get a brand new stadium at the high school.

666
01:14:24,741 --> 01:14:27,183
We do a land lease from the city and that helps to fund.

667
01:14:27,903 --> 01:14:29,904
this project instead of the debt exclusion, right?

668
01:14:29,924 --> 01:14:31,465
And I know that's something that's been brought up.

669
01:14:31,545 --> 01:14:32,745
I know that's something we're talking about.

670
01:14:33,225 --> 01:14:41,269
And I think we just can't get stuck in this thing where it's MSBA will only cover X and the rest is on the taxpayers on the debt exclusion.

671
01:14:41,289 --> 01:14:49,372
And that's the thing where I think being worried about how do we keep the cost as low as possible while doing all the things we need to do, that's right on.

672
01:14:49,892 --> 01:14:54,394
Getting into this trap of there's no chance that there's any other way to help fund this project.

673
01:14:54,574 --> 01:14:56,735
I think that's something that I'm hearing more of.

674
01:14:57,475 --> 01:14:59,936
And I'm worried about, you know, kind of dominating the conversation.

675
01:14:59,957 --> 01:15:05,960
Because I think there's so many ways that we can, that you guys are working to bring the price down and still do what we need to do.

676
01:15:06,200 --> 01:15:11,143
And other ways to fund the project other than just say, throw up our hands, the only solution is the debt exclusion.

677
01:15:11,723 --> 01:15:13,184
It's going to be a big part of the solution.

678
01:15:13,204 --> 01:15:14,525
There's going to be a debt exclusion.

679
01:15:14,565 --> 01:15:18,947
But I don't think we should just say that's our only option.

680
01:15:19,007 --> 01:15:20,388
And because of that, let's cut.

681
01:15:21,373 --> 01:15:29,017
big important programs, let's cut the MFN, let's cut the pool, let's cut fields for our kids, let's, you know, cut the vocational school.

682
01:15:29,037 --> 01:15:30,218
I don't think any of us want that.

683
01:15:30,298 --> 01:15:34,040
And I think there's other ways for us to fund, you know, to fund this project.

684
01:15:34,080 --> 01:15:35,421
That means we don't have to make that decision.

685
01:15:35,501 --> 01:15:37,722
So I hope we can have those big conversations.

686
01:15:37,782 --> 01:15:42,304
And to me, that's like the one thing that this body might be able to help you guys with.

687
01:15:42,344 --> 01:15:43,805
Don't worry, you're on my list.

688
01:15:44,646 --> 01:15:46,987
So just want to, I just really think that's important.

689
01:15:47,027 --> 01:15:48,448
I think we're getting a little

690
01:15:49,976 --> 01:15:53,317
some of the cost conversations not being creative enough.

691
01:15:53,738 --> 01:16:00,600
I think the other thing about the cost conversation is like, we have one estimate, right, so far.

692
01:16:01,281 --> 01:16:07,583
And that one estimate was done by two different independent cost estimating firms.

693
01:16:08,943 --> 01:16:11,266
The next set of cost estimates, they'll have more inputs.

694
01:16:11,847 --> 01:16:14,991
The same two firms are gonna go down the same road.

695
01:16:15,451 --> 01:16:27,507
But at this early stage, there's so many variables that they cannot control for, and it's a bad time in our world to be reliant on things that come from other countries, right?

696
01:16:28,097 --> 01:16:30,359
This week there's a tariff, next week there's not.

697
01:16:30,699 --> 01:16:32,040
The week after that there's a tariff.

698
01:16:32,600 --> 01:16:40,105
All of that sort of feeds the economic picture of like how they're having to cost for this.

699
01:16:40,706 --> 01:16:42,347
The estimators, they do this for a living.

700
01:16:42,807 --> 01:16:50,513
None of them wants to be known as the firm that undershot the estimate, right?

701
01:16:51,273 --> 01:16:55,676
So that means all of the conservatism is gonna be there right now.

702
01:16:55,757 --> 01:16:57,178
And as we go forward,

703
01:16:57,958 --> 01:17:01,620
more things will come into focus, the timing, all of those things comes into focus.

704
01:17:03,181 --> 01:17:04,481
They can be more precise.

705
01:17:04,942 --> 01:17:14,767
When we bring on our construction manager at risk, they will help us through the late stages of cost estimating during schematic design.

706
01:17:15,167 --> 01:17:20,750
So the construction manager who's going to build the project, who's going to ultimately agree to a maximum price

707
01:17:21,270 --> 01:17:24,293
will be there with us doing those estimates.

708
01:17:24,393 --> 01:17:42,170
So they're going to have a completely different point of view than an architecture firm is about how to accelerate the project, how to phase the project, how to keep costs in line, what the tradeoffs are, where the efficiencies are, where the economies of scales are.

709
01:17:42,490 --> 01:17:45,552
So all of that is to come from a cost perspective.

710
01:17:45,632 --> 01:17:50,976
And we just have to, we just all sort of have to hang on for the ride as that happens.

711
01:17:52,337 --> 01:17:58,121
But to your point, the other conversation that is a huge evolution is like, where will the money come from?

712
01:17:58,181 --> 01:17:58,981
Like, you know,

713
01:17:59,822 --> 01:18:01,123
Well, fam, they're my heroes.

714
01:18:01,183 --> 01:18:03,704
They did their whole high school without a debt exclusion.

715
01:18:03,744 --> 01:18:04,904
Like, that's not us.

716
01:18:05,084 --> 01:18:06,385
We're not going to be able to do that here.

717
01:18:07,926 --> 01:18:10,087
But what can we do?

718
01:18:10,147 --> 01:18:15,209
Like, we successfully did a capital campaign for the Medford Library, right?

719
01:18:15,289 --> 01:18:16,950
So is there a capital campaign?

720
01:18:17,490 --> 01:18:25,434
Are there grants that we can apply for and we already have to start to help pay for some portions of this program?

721
01:18:25,870 --> 01:18:29,751
Can we tap into our CPC funding for the green open space?

722
01:18:30,252 --> 01:18:42,016
What are all the things that we can do to leave no stone unturned and not have the debt exclusion be the whole only answer?

723
01:18:42,036 --> 01:18:53,440
I don't personally see a way that it won't be a part of the answer, but I think the conversation can be more nuanced if we're willing to go for that ride.

724
01:18:55,140 --> 01:18:58,882
And yes, we'll be knocking on your door to do that soon enough, I'm sure.

725
01:19:00,723 --> 01:19:00,943
Great.

726
01:19:01,363 --> 01:19:01,743
Thank you.

727
01:19:04,044 --> 01:19:04,424
All right.

728
01:19:05,125 --> 01:19:07,786
Do we have any more questions about the high school?

729
01:19:07,826 --> 01:19:09,006
You want to talk about Missituck?

730
01:19:09,207 --> 01:19:12,948
And we'll come back around at the end of the paper for public participation.

731
01:19:12,968 --> 01:19:13,769
Okay.

732
01:19:14,009 --> 01:19:19,731
Let's finish the presentation on the accelerated repair projects, ongoing, future, present, past.

733
01:19:20,051 --> 01:19:20,151
Yeah.

734
01:19:20,171 --> 01:19:20,331
Sure.

735
01:19:21,152 --> 01:19:23,553
So there's still lots of

736
01:19:24,255 --> 01:19:26,016
projects going on at the other five schools we have.

737
01:19:26,636 --> 01:19:33,998
So we've been recently accepted to the accelerated repair program by the Mass School Building Authority for the Brooks, the Mississippi, and the Roberts.

738
01:19:34,778 --> 01:19:42,321
This repair program would encompass a roof refurbishment or replacement as well as replacement of our aging HVAC systems.

739
01:19:42,881 --> 01:19:52,429
These systems that they would look to replace would study ground source or air source instead of gas or electric to be the source of the energy for these buildings.

740
01:19:53,349 --> 01:20:01,436
The Roberts School was the first school to be accepted in, and we have an engineer and an OPM on staff already.

741
01:20:01,856 --> 01:20:10,403
They were actually, had a whole team of engineers out at the Roberts studying it over April vacation, pouring through the plans, looking through the building, taking measurements,

742
01:20:10,983 --> 01:20:16,926
and they're working together to get us to a proposed project that would do that, do those tasks.

743
01:20:17,487 --> 01:20:21,849
We are in the early stages of the Missituck and the Brooks.

744
01:20:21,929 --> 01:20:28,313
The Missituck will be the next one that we'll start off, and then we'll go to the Brooks after that.

745
01:20:28,393 --> 01:20:32,275
They'll be almost identical projects because the buildings are very similar.

746
01:20:32,295 --> 01:20:37,198
They were all built at the same time, but you have to study each one individually and move forward with that.

747
01:20:40,462 --> 01:20:50,005
The, our OPM is a firm called PCA 360, and the engineer is a company called Rist Frost Shumway.

748
01:20:51,266 --> 01:21:00,849
Their draft schedule is that they'll have something ready for us by June and early July as an early plan of what they expect.

749
01:21:01,309 --> 01:21:06,051
We'll be bringing a schematic design over the summer and bringing that to the school committee in late August.

750
01:21:06,691 --> 01:21:10,455
and be ready to submit something to the August MSBA.

751
01:21:10,475 --> 01:21:15,059
We have to submit it in August for the October MSBA board meeting.

752
01:21:15,639 --> 01:21:22,206
Once we do that, they'll come back with a project funding agreement, and then we'd come back to the city to seek funding for that first project.

753
01:21:23,427 --> 01:21:29,893
That project would likely last a year or two, most of the work being done in the summers because, of course, school is in session.

754
01:21:31,272 --> 01:21:32,793
and then we'd move on from there.

755
01:21:33,534 --> 01:21:36,856
So we probably may be able to start construction in the summer of 27.

756
01:21:37,116 --> 01:21:42,179
That's a very aggressive schedule for the Roberts, but we'll see how that works out.

757
01:21:44,721 --> 01:21:53,287
The Missituck actually, their program commenced on March 2nd, which just means that we kick off our paperwork portion of the program.

758
01:21:53,987 --> 01:22:03,933
We'll be seeking our funding to authorize that feasibility study go forward, as well as the Brooks will be commencing in the beginning of July.

759
01:22:07,014 --> 01:22:16,760
And I think the other thing worth mentioning is the vote that you all will take tonight would authorize funding for Missituck and Brooks in one paper.

760
01:22:17,340 --> 01:22:19,421
That doesn't change the timing of any of this.

761
01:22:19,501 --> 01:22:24,884
It just means we don't have to come and ask you to take the same vote three times.

762
01:22:24,924 --> 01:22:26,305
We'll just do it the two times.

763
01:22:27,005 --> 01:22:36,391
And the amounts in the paper are reflective of what we were able to learn from the first project at the Roberts so that we feel like those are the right numbers.

764
01:22:38,007 --> 01:22:42,150
and in lower numbers than what we had planned for with the Roberts.

765
01:22:47,733 --> 01:22:54,176
At the McGlynn and the Andrews, there's the $25 million HVAC project that was going on there since last summer.

766
01:22:55,117 --> 01:23:00,900
That project is doing an air source, heating and air conditioning system for both buildings.

767
01:23:01,020 --> 01:23:03,001
It's replacing the roof at the McGlynn.

768
01:23:03,501 --> 01:23:06,363
The Andrews roof was already replaced, making them both solar ready.

769
01:23:07,400 --> 01:23:12,962
The accelerated repair programs also make those buildings solar ready, I forgot to mention that.

770
01:23:13,842 --> 01:23:27,546
So the project is scheduled to be substantial completion by the end of the summer, early September, in which case then we'll follow immediately with the McGlynn roofing project to get that as a liquid applied roofing system that will apply over the top of the McGlynn roof.

771
01:23:28,447 --> 01:23:35,329
The solar installation for the Andrews will start first and then the McGlynn will move on after that.

772
01:23:36,149 --> 01:23:40,894
We had a really big week last week during April vacation for both buildings.

773
01:23:41,054 --> 01:23:56,048
The new rooftop units were all activated and we transitioned to those new rooftop units over April vacation, getting us ready to be able to kick off the air conditioning season with the brand new systems ready and online by mid-May on schedule.

774
01:23:56,808 --> 01:24:01,330
The contractor, Consigli, has been wonderful to work with, working very, very hard with us.

775
01:24:02,150 --> 01:24:06,612
They also did a lot of site work because of the cost of the project.

776
01:24:06,632 --> 01:24:08,732
So a lot of ADA issues were kicked off.

777
01:24:08,772 --> 01:24:12,794
So they had to pour all new concrete patios.

778
01:24:13,174 --> 01:24:15,775
They had to do work in bathrooms with landings and different things.

779
01:24:15,815 --> 01:24:17,095
So they're doing a lot of work.

780
01:24:17,115 --> 01:24:24,778
They've been a really great partner working with us and collaborating with the principals to make sure that the project goes with the least impact to the students as possible.

781
01:24:29,872 --> 01:24:32,335
I think that's it for that.

782
01:24:32,375 --> 01:24:32,696
All right.

783
01:24:33,317 --> 01:24:34,238
If we could stop sharing.

784
01:24:34,278 --> 01:24:37,402
Do we have any questions on the elementary school and middle school projects?

785
01:24:42,209 --> 01:24:42,870
From the council.

786
01:24:43,050 --> 01:24:43,611
Just a second.

787
01:24:43,731 --> 01:24:45,032
We'll go to public participation.

788
01:24:45,073 --> 01:24:45,233
Yeah.

789
01:24:46,854 --> 01:24:51,735
I just wanted to say it's like all six of our schools are in MSBA right now.

790
01:24:51,815 --> 01:24:52,995
That is Herculean.

791
01:24:53,176 --> 01:24:55,156
Well, the McGlynn and Andrews are not an MSBA project.

792
01:24:55,236 --> 01:24:56,256
Oh, those are just us.

793
01:24:56,336 --> 01:24:56,756
Oh, great.

794
01:24:57,016 --> 01:24:57,176
Yeah.

795
01:24:57,537 --> 01:24:58,177
Okay.

796
01:24:58,477 --> 01:25:07,859
Yeah, and I think when we submitted the statements of interest for the three elementary schools, we did not think that we would get all three awards.

797
01:25:08,339 --> 01:25:10,920
And MSBA has moved to only funding those every other year.

798
01:25:12,082 --> 01:25:27,218
We're really, I think, fortunate that we did get them all because now we can sequence the projects and make sure we don't hit the point of failure on any of those systems where if we had to, if we only got one, we had to wait two more years to submit and then a year for that process to kick off.

799
01:25:27,698 --> 01:25:31,742
We are at the end of life with all of these units and systems.

800
01:25:33,143 --> 01:25:41,306
We won't have to foot the whole bill of any of those projects like we had to do with McGlynn and Andrews.

801
01:25:41,486 --> 01:25:51,389
So, yeah, it's really fortunate that we were able to get all three projects through the pipeline at the same time while actively having the high school project going on.

802
01:25:51,590 --> 01:25:52,850
So, we're really lucky.

803
01:25:53,010 --> 01:25:53,590
It's impressive.

804
01:25:53,890 --> 01:25:57,832
And, you know, major work on every school building all at once is significant.

805
01:25:58,992 --> 01:26:01,273
In terms of the life cycle, you know,

806
01:26:03,307 --> 01:26:05,348
We're 25 years from the quote-unquote new schools, right?

807
01:26:05,508 --> 01:26:08,290
They opened in 2001 and 2003, I think.

808
01:26:09,751 --> 01:26:10,612
So we're there.

809
01:26:10,892 --> 01:26:14,175
Do these projects for those buildings, is that a 25-year project?

810
01:26:14,455 --> 01:26:15,536
Are we thinking a bit differently?

811
01:26:15,576 --> 01:26:17,677
They might last us a bit longer than that.

812
01:26:19,519 --> 01:26:20,219
How do we look at that?

813
01:26:20,719 --> 01:26:24,923
I think the heating and air conditioning systems, you're looking at like a 25-year lifespan on those types of systems.

814
01:26:25,283 --> 01:26:30,927
What these projects are doing is being able to extend the lifespan of those buildings by making sure you get the roofs done and properly, yeah.

815
01:26:31,421 --> 01:26:31,581
Right.

816
01:26:31,901 --> 01:26:32,161
Okay.

817
01:26:32,341 --> 01:26:35,222
So at least gets us another 25 years in our five schools.

818
01:26:36,043 --> 01:26:44,586
And then there's also our facilities condition assessment report which we did, was done last year, which really did a thorough investigation of all the buildings, looking at all the capital projects.

819
01:26:46,606 --> 01:26:51,388
Pursuing those projects will also extend the life of those buildings and make them, you know, last properly.

820
01:26:52,465 --> 01:26:54,005
Great, well, I appreciate that.

821
01:26:54,045 --> 01:26:59,807
I think that's some work that's long overdue for our city to make sure that these investments that we make last.

822
01:27:00,507 --> 01:27:01,448
So I'm glad that we're doing it.

823
01:27:02,508 --> 01:27:09,950
All right, any further questions from members of the council on the MSBA projects for the high school and the elementary schools or the middle school project?

824
01:27:11,231 --> 01:27:13,651
All right, we will go to public participation.

825
01:27:14,772 --> 01:27:18,833
You can raise your hand on Zoom or come to the podium and you will have three minutes.

826
01:27:22,203 --> 01:27:23,504
Name and address for the record, please.

827
01:27:23,844 --> 01:27:24,785
Good evening, everyone.

828
01:27:24,825 --> 01:27:28,047
Sharon Diesso, Mass Avenue, Circuit Road in Medford.

829
01:27:28,748 --> 01:27:32,790
Pardon the garb, I ran from the yard forgetting that this meeting was going on.

830
01:27:33,811 --> 01:27:40,456
I'll give you all a wave because the Queen is here and the King is here having dinner at the White House tonight, so I'll give you all the Queens.

831
01:27:41,236 --> 01:27:45,741
wave, I just wanted to ask a quick question.

832
01:27:46,442 --> 01:27:55,693
I knew a couple of years ago that the school talk was in the works, that people were saying, we're going to get a new school, they're going to knock our school down.

833
01:27:56,694 --> 01:28:05,021
You know, you have to look at the big picture, and I hope that some of the public does go to the meetings because our future is from our youth.

834
01:28:05,842 --> 01:28:11,907
I just had a couple of questions for anyone who might know or someone who just gave a nice presentation.

835
01:28:11,927 --> 01:28:16,631
I would imagine what prompted all of this need was probably safety.

836
01:28:17,472 --> 01:28:19,073
I know, like the library,

837
01:28:21,475 --> 01:28:24,117
had a lot of electrical issues, et cetera.

838
01:28:24,658 --> 01:28:29,822
So I'm imagining that safety prompted a lot of this and then further investigation.

839
01:28:30,643 --> 01:28:36,789
A lot of the people are unsure exactly in the public, and some friends, exactly how old that building is.

840
01:28:36,809 --> 01:28:38,070
I taught in that building.

841
01:28:38,950 --> 01:28:49,855
I know the first floor is extremely, extremely maintained and very sound because it leads to a lot of administrative offices in the libraries, guidance departments, et cetera.

842
01:28:50,316 --> 01:28:55,918
And as those needs grew, those accommodations were made and done over very, very nicely.

843
01:28:55,938 --> 01:28:59,440
So I'm hoping we don't have to lose any of that first floor.

844
01:29:02,341 --> 01:29:15,244
I know that in one or two of the elementary schools, I'm hoping that in their study that they looked over dynamics of student new enrollment coming in through the next, I would say, 20 years.

845
01:29:16,485 --> 01:29:17,365
I think it's shrinking.

846
01:29:18,005 --> 01:29:26,247
So I don't know if they've compared this need to other towns who have been questioning the same thing and I'm hoping that they have enrollment

847
01:29:26,707 --> 01:29:37,357
in mind so that we don't just over-ideologically build because we have a philosophy in mind of what a school should be like rather than what are our needs.

848
01:29:38,559 --> 01:29:44,765
Thirdly, I'd like to address the fact that a lot of buildings, even like for instance the library in Winchester,

849
01:29:45,385 --> 01:29:49,388
They've built up, they've built out, they've revamped beautifully.

850
01:29:49,829 --> 01:29:57,735
I have to say I go there and visit sometimes as much as I do Medford because I enjoy what Winchester has done also with their space.

851
01:30:05,160 --> 01:30:20,329
I would like to know what the needs would be that focused beyond the safety and is prompting some of this building that would be going on.

852
01:30:22,070 --> 01:30:24,631
I think they said they will get down to one option.

853
01:30:26,592 --> 01:30:27,773
That's really not an option.

854
01:30:28,173 --> 01:30:35,917
And it said, just 10 more seconds, that this would be voted on by the city, what is meant by the word city, who will be voting on that.

855
01:30:36,398 --> 01:30:37,578
And that's really not a vote.

856
01:30:37,738 --> 01:30:45,863
If that's the only option that you have and the project's going to go forward, if it's going to be done by the public, you should have at least two or three options that they would vote on.

857
01:30:46,243 --> 01:30:47,083
It's our money too.

858
01:30:47,864 --> 01:30:50,345
Even though you get a grant, sometimes you have to match part of it.

859
01:30:50,745 --> 01:30:51,646
Thank you very much.

860
01:30:52,346 --> 01:30:52,686
Thank you.

861
01:30:52,927 --> 01:30:53,547
Thank you, Sharon.

862
01:30:53,587 --> 01:30:55,108
I think there are definitely some questions.

863
01:30:55,188 --> 01:31:01,212
I will go to the building committee chair and chief of operations for the schools.

864
01:31:01,252 --> 01:31:08,598
But just before that, you know, it is, I think we've put a lot of lipstick on the pig that is the Medford High School building.

865
01:31:09,238 --> 01:31:10,199
And, you know, it might look

866
01:31:10,979 --> 01:31:16,681
You know, it's certainly a functional space right now, but there's a lot of issues underlying the main infrastructure.

867
01:31:17,101 --> 01:31:20,883
It was built, it was opened I think in 1970, built in the late 60s.

868
01:31:20,943 --> 01:31:26,785
We're about 55 to 60, certainly probably by the time we start construction nearing 60-year-old building.

869
01:31:26,805 --> 01:31:29,786
And there's just a lot of issues at the core of it.

870
01:31:30,326 --> 01:31:35,428
Its main systems, its roof, its HVAC, the construction materials that it was built with.

871
01:31:36,329 --> 01:31:37,190
It's a tough building.

872
01:31:37,550 --> 01:31:48,502
You know, I think there are many of the options are to either renovate or partially reuse the building with varying amounts of the building falling into that.

873
01:31:49,563 --> 01:31:52,767
But there's a lot of parts of the building that it's very hard to reuse.

874
01:31:53,527 --> 01:32:07,359
It might look good in the lobby, but if you go in the back of the locker rooms, which is built kind of, it's the back of the building, built towards the hill, they are in brutal shape, like very, very deteriorated, and I think they reflect a lot of the issues.

875
01:32:08,618 --> 01:32:18,941
In terms of the approval process, so the building committee is working through the process that the state MSBA has for how you come up with a design.

876
01:32:19,361 --> 01:32:36,345
In terms of the voting of the city, that committee will present an option final after all of this design, construction, assessment, architect work, and then the voters will decide whether they want to fund that construction project.

877
01:32:36,385 --> 01:32:37,165
So at that point,

878
01:32:37,693 --> 01:32:40,378
all of the voters of the city will have a vote on the project.

879
01:32:41,099 --> 01:32:46,969
And I think everything else, you know, I'll turn it over maybe to Jenny and Ken just to get into it a little bit more.

880
01:32:51,423 --> 01:32:53,823
I'm going to try to remember them and if I forget any, just let me know.

881
01:32:54,884 --> 01:32:59,805
So the first question that I heard was about sort of like what's driving the need for this building.

882
01:33:00,685 --> 01:33:06,066
Certainly safety is obviously a really, really big important thing when you talk about a school of any kind.

883
01:33:06,946 --> 01:33:08,886
So that is definitely one of those things.

884
01:33:09,006 --> 01:33:18,048
And when we talk about safety at Medford High, we also talk about site access and circulation around the site so that our first responders have an easy

885
01:33:18,527 --> 01:33:21,431
an easy time getting on the site if they need to be there.

886
01:33:23,703 --> 01:33:34,709
More importantly, when we talk about safety, we talk about things like structural support, so the building is not code compliant with current standards around earthquake mitigation.

887
01:33:36,750 --> 01:33:45,495
All the lateral supports are not sufficient to carry a building into the future, certainly not if you're gonna put something up on top of it.

888
01:33:46,316 --> 01:33:53,000
So there's lots of safety aspects of the building that actually, the cost of all of that adds up quite quickly.

889
01:33:54,621 --> 01:33:59,687
In addition to all of that, our vocational programs are out of space and undersized.

890
01:33:59,827 --> 01:34:11,220
So we are putting more kids than is recommended by our state standards into spaces so that we can give them access to vocational programming.

891
01:34:11,927 --> 01:34:14,168
It's extraordinarily expensive to send kids out of district.

892
01:34:14,608 --> 01:34:16,188
We want to keep our students here.

893
01:34:16,608 --> 01:34:19,229
We have fabulous teachers and really great programming.

894
01:34:19,689 --> 01:34:23,490
But there is a point at which we just have to grow the wait list.

895
01:34:24,631 --> 01:34:28,092
There's also huge demand for things like plumbing, HVAC.

896
01:34:28,652 --> 01:34:30,513
criminal justice, and dental assisting.

897
01:34:30,553 --> 01:34:38,995
Those things are not just demands of our students, but when you look at the labor market in the area, those things are very, very in demand and supported.

898
01:34:39,416 --> 01:34:42,977
And we don't have space for those kinds of programs right now.

899
01:34:44,097 --> 01:34:48,379
So the expansion of those vocational programs to do two things.

900
01:34:48,699 --> 01:34:58,302
One, to mitigate the wait list, and two, to expand the program is a huge portion of this space when we talk about sort of the increase in space.

901
01:34:59,162 --> 01:35:11,207
Our special education program is another place where we have been working in woefully undersized classrooms and spaces for a really, really long time.

902
01:35:11,307 --> 01:35:13,748
Our special education population is important.

903
01:35:14,168 --> 01:35:20,170
They need something different from us to thrive, and we have a really, really hard time providing that in the current space.

904
01:35:20,190 --> 01:35:27,693
So that's another place where there is going to be a change of the amount of space that we are gonna be able to dedicate to a program under this.

905
01:35:29,261 --> 01:35:38,655
And then I think finally, when you are a student learning in this building, things like how far it is to get from one sprawling end of the building to the other.

906
01:35:40,756 --> 01:35:45,319
all of those things impede how you can access your education.

907
01:35:45,399 --> 01:35:50,282
So really thinking about a classroom in a more modern sense is really important.

908
01:35:50,342 --> 01:35:51,803
Our classrooms are actually quite small.

909
01:35:51,863 --> 01:35:57,226
So I think there's lots of myths that have perpetuated in the community, like our classrooms are really very big.

910
01:35:57,586 --> 01:35:58,247
They are not.

911
01:35:58,687 --> 01:36:04,691
They are smaller than the standards that MSBA uses to decide on the space of a classroom.

912
01:36:05,171 --> 01:36:14,897
There's all kinds of things like that where we are doing more with less already and we can't keep sort of strapping the system in that way.

913
01:36:14,997 --> 01:36:20,800
So from a what else is driving this project, all of those things are driving this project.

914
01:36:21,100 --> 01:36:30,366
And also trying to say how do we alleviate some of the pressure that we're feeling in other buildings that are at capacity?

915
01:36:30,486 --> 01:36:33,908
So we have several elementary schools that are at capacity and

916
01:36:34,409 --> 01:36:42,012
If we don't address those things in a variety of ways, this is one of the ways that we'll plan to address that.

917
01:36:42,552 --> 01:36:48,435
We will be looking at needs for expansion of some of those buildings in the next five to 10 years.

918
01:36:48,675 --> 01:36:55,218
So this project gives us an opportunity to push that off in a meaningful way.

919
01:36:55,658 --> 01:36:58,879
And there's no, like the cheapest time to do this project was 10 years ago.

920
01:36:58,899 --> 01:37:00,560
The next cheapest time is right now.

921
01:37:01,170 --> 01:37:04,152
It is not the cheapest time to do a construction project 10 years from now.

922
01:37:04,232 --> 01:37:08,595
So all of those things are sort of factoring into something fairly complicated.

923
01:37:09,681 --> 01:37:17,145
In terms of enrollment, one of the biggest parts of the process, so we actually were accepted by the MSBA in 2023.

924
01:37:18,066 --> 01:37:21,548
It feels like it's already been like a short lifetime with this project.

925
01:37:22,528 --> 01:37:33,855
But part of the work that has been happening over the last couple of years was a really detailed enrollment study that looked at Medford historically and into the future.

926
01:37:34,916 --> 01:37:40,302
It looked at everything from how our enrollment has changed over time.

927
01:37:40,722 --> 01:37:44,206
It looked at what they call a survival model of students.

928
01:37:44,446 --> 01:37:51,815
What that means is how many kindergarten students become first graders next year and second graders the year after that and third graders the year after that.

929
01:37:53,655 --> 01:37:56,536
So all of that study was done in collaboration.

930
01:37:56,576 --> 01:37:59,057
We provided lots and lots of information to the MSBA.

931
01:37:59,497 --> 01:38:11,400
They did a detailed study of our enrollment, and that is how we certified that 1,395 students are the right number for us to build for here.

932
01:38:11,840 --> 01:38:15,641
That is more students than are at the high school today.

933
01:38:17,359 --> 01:38:25,703
and that is because this building needs to last us 50 years, and there is evidence to suggest that the student population in Medford will increase by that much.

934
01:38:25,743 --> 01:38:36,188
The MSBA absolutely would not just sort of blanket give us space, like capacity in students that is not provable or warranted.

935
01:38:36,328 --> 01:38:41,330
So all of that, and there's a really detailed enrollment study that's available.

936
01:38:41,811 --> 01:38:44,772
I wrote a blog about it, so if I can send it to Sharon,

937
01:38:45,872 --> 01:38:47,893
if she wants to take a look at all the bits and parts.

938
01:38:47,953 --> 01:38:54,494
But it looked at everything from real estate in the city, planned construction, the MBTA Communities Act.

939
01:38:54,574 --> 01:39:00,216
It looked at all of the factors reasonably that we know about to come up with those numbers.

940
01:39:00,736 --> 01:39:02,596
And then the third thing was about the choices.

941
01:39:02,716 --> 01:39:06,337
So I would say we are following the MSBA process.

942
01:39:06,397 --> 01:39:09,138
We do have to pick this option before we can go

943
01:39:09,798 --> 01:39:14,361
into like a vote, so the vote that we're talking about of the community is the debt exclusion, that is next year.

944
01:39:15,221 --> 01:39:16,762
But in the meantime, you do have a say.

945
01:39:17,182 --> 01:39:18,963
Come to our meetings, you get to vote.

946
01:39:18,983 --> 01:39:21,905
There's lots of different ways we're asking people to vote and weigh in.

947
01:39:22,925 --> 01:39:29,069
And I think what we saw in terms of what the public was thinking about the 29 options really did make a difference.

948
01:39:32,130 --> 01:39:36,333
align very closely with how the options were down selected to six.

949
01:39:36,413 --> 01:39:40,836
